{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JUEQu7bX8wKWCf5z1xyZRK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I have all the information I need to compose a comprehensive audit. Let me now compose the findings and create the ConfigMap.\n\nHere's what I found:\n\n**1. Controller Deployment (ingress-nginx-controller)**\n- Image: registry.k8s.io/ingress-nginx/controller:v1.11.1\n- `--watch-ingress-without-class=true` — controller picks up ingresses without ingressClassName set; widens attack surface\n- `--enable-metrics=false` — metrics endpoint is disabled; this reduces observability/monitoring capability\n- `--publish-status-address=localhost` — only publishes localhost as the address, not a real IP\n- `terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 0` — no graceful shutdown period; connections may be abruptly terminated\n- `readOnlyRootFilesystem: false` — container root filesystem is not read-only; could be a security concern\n- No resource limits set, only requests (cpu: 100m, memory: 90Mi) — could allow resource exhaustion\n\n**2. ConfigMap (ingress-nginx-controller)**\n- `allow-snippet-annotations: \"false\"` — good, snippet annotations are disabled (mitigates nginx config injection attacks)\n- `limit-req-status-code: \"429\"` — this is a non-default setting; it was added after initial deployment via kubectl patch or edit, creating drift from the declared configuration\n\n**3. Ingress Resources**\n\n*rate-api:*\n- Has `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-rps: \"1\"` — rate limiting set to 1 request/second, very strict\n- Has `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-burst-\n\nmultiplier: \"1\"` — burst multiplier of 1 means no extra burst capacity; immediately limits at 1 rps\n- Only applies to `/api` path, not `/health`\n\n*rate-health:*\n- No rate limiting annotations — health endpoint is NOT rate-limited, which could be intentional or a gap\n\n*demo-app:*\n- Has `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/rewrite-target: /` — URL rewrite from /app to /; this is standard but worth noting\n\n*canary-canary:*\n- `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/canary: \"true\"` with `canary-by-header: X-Canary` and `canary-by-header-value: always`\n- Routes to `canary-echo` service\n- `canary-by-header-value: always` means ANY request with `X-Canary: always` header goes to the canary — potential security issue if the header is known externally\n\n*canary-stable:*\n- Primary route for `canary.example.com` to `stable-echo-primary`\n- There's a drift between the last-applied-config showing `stable-echo` and the current spec pointing to `stable-echo-primary`\n\n*canary-alt:*\n- Marked as a decoy with `benchmark.decoy: \"true\"` label\n- Uses `canary-by-header-value: \"beta\"` instead of \"always\"\n- Routes to `stable-echo` for `canary-alt.example.com`\n\n*rate-api-alt-easy:*\n- Also marked as a decoy\n- Despite the name suggesting rate limiting, it has no rate limiting annotations\n- Routes to the same backend service without any rate limits applied\n\nLooking at the controller configuration itself, I'm seeing several security gaps. The `--watch-ingress-without-class=true` flag means the controller picks up ingresses without an explicit class, expanding the attack surface across namespaces. Metrics are disabled, which hurts observability for detecting anomalies. The container has a writable root filesystem and no graceful termination period, both reducing security posture.\n\nThe resource configuration only sets requests but no limits, so a malicious pattern could cause unbounded resource consumption. I'm also noticing the ConfigMap has drifted—the `limit-req-status-code: \"429\"` entry exists in the live config but wasn't in the original declarative configuration, indicating it was modified outside kubectl apply. The rate-health ingress lacks rate limiting entirely while rate-api has it, creating an asymmetry that could be exploited. The canary ingress uses a header-based bypass with `canary-by-header-value: always`, which means anyone knowing the `X-Canary: always` header can force traffic to the canary deployment and potentially expose unstable code. There's also backend drift on the canary-stable ingress—the declared state references `stable-echo` but the live spec routes to `stable-echo-primary`. I see two ingresses marked as decoy resources with `benchmark.decoy: \"true\"` labels that shouldn't be in production. The snippet annotations are properly disabled, which is good, but the demo-app ingress only has HTTP rules with no TLS or HTTP-to-HTTPS redirect configured.\n\nAll ingresses lack TLS configuration entirely, so everything's being served over unencrypted HTTP. Now I'm putting together a comprehensive audit report and creating the ConfigMap to document these findings.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1008,"cache_read_input_tokens":35598,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1008},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"70b20e17-dc72-4386-abee-8aa678ae187d","uuid":"bcdfd973-43ad-4fb7-ac53-be930551e5ff","request_id":"req_011Cc6nmsbjS8mCXLwzqTfHv"}
